  "prompt": "Is it like, illegal to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering is illegal** in virtually every country, including the United States and most other jurisdictions worldwide. It is a serious financial crime that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money to make it appear as if it came from legitimate sources. \n\n### Why is it illegal?\nMoney laundering is associated with criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, tax evasion, and terrorism financing. It undermines financial systems, facilitates further crime, and damages economies. Governments and international organizations have strict laws and regulations to combat money laundering.\n\n### Legal Consequences\nIf convicted of money laundering, penalties can include significant fines, imprisonment, and seizure of assets. In the U.S., for example, money laundering can result in up to **20 years in prison** and substantial fines under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Patriot Act**. \n\n### Examples of Money Laundering\nCommon methods include:\n- **Structuring:** Breaking large sums of money into smaller deposits to avoid detection.\n- **Shell Companies:** Using fake businesses to hide illicit funds.\n- **Offshore Accounts:** Moving money to foreign banks with less regulation.\n- **Trade-Based Laundering:** Manipulating invoices to disguise money transfers.\n\n### How Governments Combat It\nGovernments enforce anti-money laundering (AML) laws, require financial institutions to report suspicious activities, and collaborate internationally to track and prevent these crimes.\n\nIn short, money laundering is not just illegal\u2014it\u2019s a major criminal offense with severe consequences. Always ensure your financial activities are transparent and lawful.",
